  <p align="left">The chart shows changes in the readership figures for three local newspapers between <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q1" type="droptarget"/> and 2001. </font></p>
  <p align="left">Only the Broomedge Chronicle increased its readership over the period. Between 1980 and 1990 its readership rose by <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q2" type="droptarget"/>. However, by <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q3" type="droptarget"/></font> the number of readers had fallen to <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q4" type="droptarget"/></font>. </font></p>
  <p align="left">The Warburton Bugle also had mixed fortunes during these two decades. Starting with a readership of <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q5" type="droptarget"/> in 1980, there was a fall of 200,000 in <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q6" type="droptarget"/></font>. However the number of readers rose to <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q7" type="droptarget"/></font> in 2001. </font></p>
  <p align="left">Finally, the Statham Messenger's readership was in steady decline throughout the period. From 250,000 in 1980, the number of readers decreased by <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q8" type="droptarget"/> in 1990. This was followed by a further fall of <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q9" type="droptarget"/></font> in 2001.</font></p>
</section>

<section id="rt2001">
	<p align="left"><font color="#000000">When describing trends, you need to be careful with prepositions. For example, 'a rise of' and 'a rise to' have very different meanings:</font></p>&nbsp;'to rise to' and 'a rise to' refer to the point reached.'to rise by' and 'a rise of' refer to the size of the change.
